<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-11T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-11T07:00:00-05:00" n="627" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d627">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">751.61/313: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-11T12:00:00+00:00">January
                                    11, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 11—9:18
                                a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>58. There has been a considerable demand from the Eight in France
                            recently for the breaking of diplomatic relations with the Soviet
                            Union.</p>
                        <pb facs="0602" n="590" xml:id="pg_590"/>
                        <p>Coulondre<note n="66" xml:id="d627fn66">Robert Coulondre, Director of the
                                Cabinet of the Minister for Foreign Affairs; formerly French
                                Ambassador in Germany, 1938–39.</note> stated to me yesterday that
                                Daladier<note n="67" xml:id="d627fn67">Edouard Daladier, President
                                of the French Council of Ministers until his resignation on March
                                20, 1940.</note> had now decided not to break relations with the
                            Soviet Union but to use the present wave of emotion against the
                            activities of the Soviet Union to crush the Communist agents of the
                            Soviet Union in France.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>